Overview of the dataset¶

We are using Amazon product reviews dataset.The reviews are labeled with sentiment categories: positive, neutral, or negative. This dataset is commonly used in natural language processing (NLP) tasks involving sentiment analysis.

Link to the dataset: https://github.com/3ashryy2/Amazon-Reviews-Sentiment-Analysis/tree/main

Classification Task:

The goal is to perform sentiment analysis on customer reviews, classifying each review into one of three categories positive, neutral, negative.

Business Case:

  • Customer Feedback Analysis: This can be used for insights into product performance, customer satisfaction, or service improvements.
  • Product Improvement: We can analyze negative reviews which will help to identify potential issues and improve products or services. This could help in preventing churn by proactively addressing negative feedback.
  • Market Sentiment Tracking: By analyzing positive reviews we can help business with marketing and sales strategies.
  • Presonalized Marketing & Recommendations: Sentiment analysis helps in customizing marketing messages based on customer feedback. Business can implement strategies like customer referrals, discounts, free returns, etc. for customer retention.

Multi Task:

This dataset is not multi-task. It focuses solely on a single task- classifying reviews based on their sentiments (positive, negative or neutral).

Feature Data

The primary feature is "cleaned_review", which has been preprocessed which includes removing stopwords, removing non-alphanumeric characters, and changing all the text to lowercase. The dataset also contains features "cleaned_review_length" and "review_score" which are not being used in this report. The target variable is "sentiments" which indicates a sentiment for a review.

The data was collected by Amazon as part of their customer feedback system. These customer reviews were submitted after making purchases by the customers on Amazon website. The data was collected from customers to express their opinions and to help businesses improve products and services based on feedback and also to know about customers preference. The dataset is from Amazon's product review system. While the exact collection date isn't specified, the reviews are continuously collected as part of Amazon's regular operations. The preprocessed dataset "amazon_reviews.csv", used in this report, was collected from the github link provided above.

Multi-Modal

No, the data is not multi-modal. It only consists text-based reviews

Evaluation Criteria

To evaluate the performance of our sentiment classification model, we will use the following key metrics:

  1. Accuracy: It measures the proportion of correctly classified reviews out of all reviews. It gives an overall sense of the models performance. As we are simply measuring how well a trined model predicts a sentiment for a review, a simple accuracy measure is reliable evaluation metric.

  2. Cross-entropy Loss (Validation Loss & Training Loss) The training loss indicates how well the model is learning during training. Lower values suggest the model is fitting well to the data. The validation loss helps detect overfittingif it remains high while training loss decreases, the model may be memorizing rather than generalizing. Cross-entropy loss is well-suited for multi-class classification problems where we are predicting probabilities across multiple categories. It also effectively penalizes incorrect confident predictions.

Business Case Support:

A high accuracy ensures the model is correctly identifying positive, neutral, and negative sentiments which will help businesses interpret overall customer satisfaction.

A lower validation loss ensures that the model generalizes well to unseen data, making sentiment predictions reliable for real-world customer reviews.

Foundational Model for Transfer Learning: BERT-base-uncased¶

For classification task, we are using BERT-base-uncased, a pretrained Transformer-based language model developed by Google.

Its a bidirectional transformer pretrained using a combination of masked language modeling objective and next sentence prediction on a large corpus comprising the Toronto Book Corpus and Wikipedia.

Masked Language Modeling(MLM): Some words in a sentence are randomly masked, and the model learns to predict them based on surrounding context. This enables deep bidirectional understanding of language.

Next Sentence Prediction (NSP): Given two sentences, the model predicts whether the second sentence follows the first. This helps in tasks that require understanding sentence relationships, such as question-answering or dialogue generation.

The new task of classification of reviews fall in same domain as BERT's pretraining. BERT was originally trained on general textual data, and sentiment classification is a text-based task. The new task, which is sentiment classification of Amazon product reviews, is also a text-based task. Since BERT already understands language structure, word relationships, and context, we can adapt it to sentiment classification with a smaller labeled dataset.

Load BERT model and tokenizer¶

We will load the pretrained BERT uncased model. We want to perform classification, so we will need to get BertForSequenceClassifiction as it includes a fully connected classification layer on top of the BERT model

Some weights of BertForSequenceClassification were not initialized from the model checkpoint at bert-base-uncased and are newly initialized: ['classifier.bias', 'classifier.weight']
You should probably TRAIN this model on a down-stream task to be able to use it for predictions and inference.

BertForSequenceClassification(
  (bert): BertModel(
    (embeddings): BertEmbeddings(
      (word_embeddings): Embedding(30522, 768, padding_idx=0)
      (position_embeddings): Embedding(512, 768)
      (token_type_embeddings): Embedding(2, 768)
      (LayerNorm): LayerNorm((768,), eps=1e-12, elementwise_affine=True)
      (dropout): Dropout(p=0.1, inplace=False)
    )
    (encoder): BertEncoder(
      (layer): ModuleList(
        (0-11): 12 x BertLayer(
          (attention): BertAttention(
            (self): BertSdpaSelfAttention(
              (query): Linear(in_features=768, out_features=768, bias=True)
              (key): Linear(in_features=768, out_features=768, bias=True)
              (value): Linear(in_features=768, out_features=768, bias=True)
              (dropout): Dropout(p=0.1, inplace=False)
            )
            (output): BertSelfOutput(
              (dense): Linear(in_features=768, out_features=768, bias=True)
              (LayerNorm): LayerNorm((768,), eps=1e-12, elementwise_affine=True)
              (dropout): Dropout(p=0.1, inplace=False)
            )
          )
          (intermediate): BertIntermediate(
            (dense): Linear(in_features=768, out_features=3072, bias=True)
            (intermediate_act_fn): GELUActivation()
          )
          (output): BertOutput(
            (dense): Linear(in_features=3072, out_features=768, bias=True)
            (LayerNorm): LayerNorm((768,), eps=1e-12, elementwise_affine=True)
            (dropout): Dropout(p=0.1, inplace=False)
          )
        )
      )
    )
    (pooler): BertPooler(
      (dense): Linear(in_features=768, out_features=768, bias=True)
      (activation): Tanh()
    )
  )
  (dropout): Dropout(p=0.1, inplace=False)
  (classifier): Linear(in_features=768, out_features=3, bias=True)
)

Base model architecture:

  • We have BERT model that contains embeddings, word_embeddings, position_embeddings, token_type_embeddings, LayerNorm, and dropout
  • It then goes into BertEncoder that is simply 12 identical layers where we have self attention layer, query, key, value, and dropout
  • Then it goes through couple of dense layers: output "BertSelfOutput, intermediate "BertIntermediate", and output "BertOutput
  • Then it goes through a pooling layer "BertPooler" that has output of 768 (linear)
  • Finally it goes through a classifier layer (untrained) that expects intput of 768 and will have output of 20 (number of layers for classification)

Since there are some reviews that have more than 512 tokens, we will need to truncate them to 512 tokens to be used for BERT model.

In [49]:
max_tokens = 512

# list to store each sample as a dictionary that contains tokenized review and corresponding label
encoded_dataset = []

# to count samples processed
samples_processed = 0

# Map the text labels to integers
label_map = {"negative":0, "neutral":1, "positive":2}


# iterate through each sample in the dataset_final
for text, label in tqdm(zip(dataset_final['cleaned_review'], dataset_final['sentiments']), desc="Encoding", total=len(dataset_final['sentiments'])):

    # Tokenize the text with truncation and padding. Returned as PyTorch tensors
    encoded_example = tokenizer(text, return_tensors='pt',
                                truncation=True,
                                padding='max_length',
                                max_length=max_tokens)

    # Convert the string labels to integer labels as mapped above
    encoded_example['label_id'] = label_map.get(label)

    # Check if the tokenized sequence length is correct
    assert len(encoded_example.input_ids[0]) == max_tokens

    # Add the encoded example to the dataset_final
    encoded_dataset.append(encoded_example)

We can see the encoded dictionary with keys input_ids, token_type_ids, attention_maks, and label_id with their tensors as their values. All of them have been padded to 512 tokens.

Now we will setup tracking for training and validation loss. We will freeze all the layers of BERT first. Unfreeze the last pooling layer of BERT and its classifier layer. Then we will add them to be passed to the optimzer before being trained.

In [ ]:
# setup tracking.
history_base = {}  # empty dict to store training history of the base model
history_base['val_loss'] = []  # stores validation loss values
history_base['train_loss'] = []  # stores training loss values

epochs = 3

# Go thru all parameters of the model and freeze entire model initially.
for param in model_base.parameters():
    param.requires_grad = False

# only train the parameters for pooler layer of BERT (final layer before our classifier layer)
for param in model_base.bert.pooler.parameters():
    param.requires_grad = True

# only train the classifier layer that we added to BERT model
for param in model_base.classifier.parameters():
    param.requires_grad = True

# now add the lists of the parameters from pooler layer and classifier layer to pass them through optimizer
train_params = list(model_base.bert.pooler.parameters()) + list(model_base.classifier.parameters())

# we can now tell the optimizer to only optimize these parameters in the model
optimizer = Adam(train_params)

Training and Evaluation datasets using Random Split¶

Create a tensor dataset from our dataset_final that takes all of the tensors from input text and labels, and combine them into a single dataset object. This ensures that all the required inputs for our BERT model are packaged together and we can do batch processing.

We are using a simple random split of 80-20 (80% as training) for splitting the dataset into training and testing datasets. 17,321 samples is not massive compared to datasets BERT was originally trained on. A simple train-test split can be effective since fine-tuning BERT does not require extremely large datasets. The dataset could be slightly imblanaced but we can still use this normal split method to keep it simple and less computational.

In [34]:
Batch_size = 16

print(f"Created two datasets training/eval. Training samples: {train_size}, Evaluation: {eval_size}")

Train baseline BERT model¶

Next, we will train our model for certain number of epochs. While training, we will track the training loss. After each epoch, we will evaluate the model's performance on the validation set. This validation loss will also be tracked. We will save the loss values for training and validation for future analysis.

In [38]:
# setting up a progress bar for epochs
with trange(epochs, desc="Epoch") as pbar:

    for epoch in pbar:
        model_base.train()  # put the model in training mode
        total_loss  = 0.0  # track the training loss

        # iterate over training data in batchs using train_dataloader.
        for batch in tqdm(train_dataloader, desc=f"Training {epoch}", total=int(train_size/Batch_size)+1, leave=False):

            # send batch (tuple of below input parameters & labels) to GPU and separate for the model
            batch = tuple(s.to(device) for s in batch)
            input_ids, input_mask, input_types, labels = batch  # unpack those parameters of the tuple

            # pass these parameters thru model to perform forward pass. This will compute model's output (includes training loss)
            output = model_base(input_ids=input_ids, attention_mask=input_mask, labels=labels)

            # back propagation
            output.loss.backward() # computes gradients by backpropagation using the loss
            optimizer.step() # use gradients in optimizer to update model's parameters
            optimizer.zero_grad() # clear out gradients of optimized tensors to avoid accumulation of gradients between different batches

            # keep track of total train loss. Need to multiply loss per sample by batch size for total loss
            total_loss += output.loss.item() * Batch_size

        # calcualte the avg. training loss and add it to the train_loss
        total_loss  = total_loss / train_size
        history_base['train_loss'].append(total_loss)

        # print the train loss in the progress bar for the epochs
        pbar.set_postfix(loss=f"{total_loss:.2f}")

        # at end of epoch, report the evaluation
        model_base.eval()  # Set model to evaluation mode (droput layers and other training specific operations are turned off)
        total_loss  = 0.0  #rest the total loss to 0 to track the validation loss

        # turn of gradient calculation as we're only evaluating the model
        with torch.no_grad():

            # evaluation in batches (same as above)
            for batch in tqdm(eval_dataloader, desc=f"Evaluating {epoch}", total=int(eval_size/Batch_size)+1, leave=False):
                batch = tuple(s.to(device) for s in batch) # send to GPU
                input_ids, input_mask, input_types, labels = batch
                output = model_base(input_ids, input_types, input_mask, labels=labels)
                total_loss += output.loss.item() * Batch_size

            total_loss  = total_loss / eval_size
            history_base['val_loss'].append(total_loss)

        # print the eval loss in the progress bar for the epochs
        pbar.set_postfix(loss=f"{total_loss:.2f}")

Train the model¶

In [184]:
# Store training times
Base_model_running_time = []

# Perform Stratified K-Fold Cross-Validation
for fold, (train_idx, eval_idx) in enumerate(scv.split(input_ids, labels_np)):
    
    print(f"\n--- Fold {fold + 1}/{n_splits} ---")

    # Subset dataset using train and eval indices
    train_data = Subset(all_data_tensors, train_idx)
    eval_data = Subset(all_data_tensors, eval_idx)

    # Create DataLoaders
    train_dataloader = DataLoader(train_data, sampler=RandomSampler(train_data), batch_size=Batch_size)
    eval_dataloader = DataLoader(eval_data, sampler=SequentialSampler(eval_data), batch_size=Batch_size)

    # Reinitialize model for each fold
    model_base.to(device)
    
    # Start timing
    start_time = time.time()

    with trange(epochs, desc=f"Epoch (Fold {fold + 1})") as pbar:
        for epoch in pbar:
            model_base.train()
            total_loss = 0.0
            
            # iterate over training data in batchs using train_dataloader.
            for batch in tqdm(train_dataloader, desc=f"Training {epoch}", total=len(train_dataloader), leave=False):
                
                batch = tuple(s.to(device) for s in batch)
                input_ids, input_mask, input_types, labels = batch

                output = model_base(input_ids=input_ids, attention_mask=input_mask, labels=labels)

                # Backpropagation
                output.loss.backward()
                optimizer.step()
                optimizer.zero_grad()

                total_loss += output.loss.item() * Batch_size

            total_loss = total_loss / len(train_dataloader.dataset)
            history_scv['train_loss'].append(total_loss)
            pbar.set_postfix(loss=f"{total_loss:.2f}")

            # Evaluation
            model_base.eval()
            total_loss = 0.0

            with torch.no_grad():
                for batch in tqdm(eval_dataloader, desc=f"Evaluating {epoch}", total=len(eval_dataloader), leave=False):
                    batch = tuple(s.to(device) for s in batch)
                    input_ids, input_mask, input_types, labels = batch

                    output = model_base(input_ids, input_types, input_mask, labels=labels)
                    total_loss += output.loss.item() * Batch_size

            total_loss = total_loss / len(eval_dataloader.dataset)
            history_scv['val_loss'].append(total_loss)
            pbar.set_postfix(val_loss=f"{total_loss:.2f}")
    
    # End timing
    end_time = time.time()
    fold_time_base = end_time - start_time
    Base_model_running_time.append(fold_time_base)
    print(f"Training time for Fold {fold + 1}: {fold_time_base:.2f} seconds")

print("\nCross-validation complete!")
print("Base model runing times (seconds):", Base_model_running_time)

So based on this assessment, we can say that using stratified cross validation is a better approach for splitting the dataset into training and testing.

    model_base.eval()  # Set model to evaluation mode

    eval_data_scv = torch.utils.data.Subset(all_data_tensors, eval_idx)
    eval_sampler_scv = SequentialSampler(eval_data_scv)
    eval_dataloader_scv = DataLoader(eval_data_scv, sampler=eval_sampler_scv, batch_size=Batch_size)

    fold_preds_base = []  # Store predictions for this fold
    fold_labels_base = []  # Store true labels for this fold

    # Run evaluation without tracking gradients
    with torch.no_grad():
        for batch in tqdm(eval_dataloader_scv, desc=f"Evaluating Fold {fold + 1}", total=int(len(eval_data_scv)/Batch_size)+1):

            batch = tuple(s.to(device) for s in batch)  # Move batch to GPU/CPU
            input_ids, input_mask, input_types, labels = batch

            # Forward pass (ensure correct argument names)
            output = model_base(input_ids=input_ids, attention_mask=input_mask, labels=None)

            # Store predictions and labels
            fold_preds_base.append(output.logits.detach().cpu().numpy())
            fold_labels_base.append(labels.cpu().numpy())

    # Store predictions per fold
    all_preds_base.append(np.concatenate(fold_preds_base, axis=0))  # Convert list of batches to array
    all_labels_base.append(np.concatenate(fold_labels_base, axis=0))  # Convert list of labels to array

Now we will unfreeze last two BERT layers, pooling layer, and classifier layer.
The weights in the last two layers wil be fine-tuned. Unfreezing the pooling layer allows us to get fixed-sized representation of the input for downstream tasks. Finally, the classifier layer is unfrozen so that it can be trained to adapt the features of our sentiment classification task. At this point, we are only training the new model using the bottleneck features.

In [140]:
# Freeze the entire model initially
for param in model_new.parameters():
    param.requires_grad = False

# Unfreeze the last 2 layers of BERT
for layer in model_new.bert.encoder.layer[-2:]:
    for param in layer.parameters():
        param.requires_grad = True

# Also unfreeze the pooler (final layer before classifier)
for param in model_new.bert.pooler.parameters():
    param.requires_grad = True

# Unfreeze the classifier layer, as we want to modify or retrain it for our new task
for param in model_new.classifier.parameters():
    param.requires_grad = True
    
# Similar to before collect trainable parameters: last 2 BERT layers, pooler layer, and classifier layer
train_params_new = (
    list(model_new.bert.encoder.layer[-2:].parameters()) +  # Last 2 BERT layers
    list(model_new.bert.pooler.parameters()) +  # Pooler layer
    list(model_new.classifier.parameters())  # Final classifier layer
)

# we can now tell the optimizer to only optimize these parameters in the model
optimizer_new = Adam(train_params_new)

# Store training times
New_model_running_time = []

# track the training and validation losses
history_scv_new = {'train_loss_new': [], 'val_loss_new': []}

# Perform Stratified K-Fold Cross-Validation
for fold, (train_idx, eval_idx) in enumerate(scv.split(input_ids, labels_np)):
    
    print(f"\n--- Fold {fold + 1}/{n_splits} ---")

    # Subset dataset using train and eval indices
    train_data = Subset(all_data_tensors, train_idx)
    eval_data = Subset(all_data_tensors, eval_idx)

    # Create DataLoaders
    train_dataloader = DataLoader(train_data, sampler=RandomSampler(train_data), batch_size=Batch_size)
    eval_dataloader = DataLoader(eval_data, sampler=SequentialSampler(eval_data), batch_size=Batch_size)

    # Reinitialize the new model for each fold
    model_new.to(device)

    # Start timing
    start_time = time.time()
    
    with trange(epochs, desc=f"Epoch (Fold {fold + 1})") as pbar:
        for epoch in pbar:
            model_new.train()
            total_loss_new = 0.0
            
            # iterate over training data in batchs using train_dataloader.
            for batch in tqdm(train_dataloader, desc=f"Training {epoch}", total=len(train_dataloader), leave=False):
                
                batch = tuple(s.to(device) for s in batch)
                input_ids, input_mask, input_types, labels = batch

                output = model_base(input_ids=input_ids, attention_mask=input_mask, labels=labels)

                # Backpropagation
                output.loss.backward()
                optimizer.step()
                optimizer.zero_grad()

                total_loss_new += output.loss.item() * Batch_size

            total_loss_new = total_loss_new / len(train_dataloader.dataset)
            history_scv_new['train_loss_new'].append(total_loss_new)
            pbar.set_postfix(loss=f"{total_loss_new:.2f}")

            # Evaluation
            model_new.eval()
            total_loss_new = 0.0

            with torch.no_grad():
                for batch in tqdm(eval_dataloader, desc=f"Evaluating {epoch}", total=len(eval_dataloader), leave=False):
                    batch = tuple(s.to(device) for s in batch)
                    input_ids, input_mask, input_types, labels = batch

                    output = model_new(input_ids, input_types, input_mask, labels=labels)
                    total_loss_new += output.loss.item() * Batch_size

            total_loss_new = total_loss_new / len(eval_dataloader.dataset)
            history_scv_new['val_loss_new'].append(total_loss_new)
            pbar.set_postfix(val_loss=f"{total_loss_new:.2f}")

    # End timing
    end_time = time.time()
    fold_time_new_model = end_time - start_time
    New_model_running_time.append(fold_time_new_model)
    print(f"Training time for Fold {fold + 1}: {fold_time_new_model:.2f} seconds")
    
print("\nCross-validation complete!")
print("New model training time (seconds):", New_model_running_time)

    # Subset dataset using train and eval indices
    train_data = Subset(all_data_tensors, train_idx)
    eval_data = Subset(all_data_tensors, eval_idx)

    # Create DataLoaders
    train_dataloader = DataLoader(train_data, sampler=RandomSampler(train_data), batch_size=Batch_size)
    eval_dataloader = DataLoader(eval_data, sampler=SequentialSampler(eval_data), batch_size=Batch_size)

    # Reinitialize the new model for each fold
    model_new_1.to(device)
    
    # Start timing
    start_time = time.time()

    with trange(epochs, desc=f"Epoch (Fold {fold + 1})") as pbar:
        for epoch in pbar:
            model_new_1.train()
            total_loss_new_1 = 0.0
            
            # iterate over training data in batchs using train_dataloader.
            for batch in tqdm(train_dataloader, desc=f"Training {epoch}", total=len(train_dataloader), leave=False):
                
                batch = tuple(s.to(device) for s in batch)
                input_ids, input_mask, input_types, labels = batch

                output = model_new_1(input_ids=input_ids, attention_mask=input_mask, labels=labels)

                # Backpropagation
                output.loss.backward()
                optimizer.step()
                optimizer.zero_grad()

                total_loss_new_1 += output.loss.item() * Batch_size

            total_loss_new_1 = total_loss_new_1 / len(train_dataloader.dataset)
            history_scv_new_1['train_loss_new_1'].append(total_loss_new_1)
            pbar.set_postfix(loss=f"{total_loss_new_1:.2f}")

            # Evaluation
            model_new_1.eval()
            total_loss_new_1 = 0.0

            with torch.no_grad():
                for batch in tqdm(eval_dataloader, desc=f"Evaluating {epoch}", total=len(eval_dataloader), leave=False):
                    batch = tuple(s.to(device) for s in batch)
                    input_ids, input_mask, input_types, labels = batch

                    output = model_new_1(input_ids, input_types, input_mask, labels=labels)
                    total_loss_new_1 += output.loss.item() * Batch_size

            total_loss_new_1 = total_loss_new_1 / len(eval_dataloader.dataset)
            history_scv_new_1['val_loss_new_1'].append(total_loss_new_1)
            pbar.set_postfix(val_loss=f"{total_loss_new_1:.2f}")

    # End timing
    end_time = time.time()
    fold_time_finetuned = end_time - start_time
    New_fine_tuned_train_time.append(fold_time_finetuned)
    print(f"Training time for Fold {fold + 1}: {fold_time_finetuned:.2f} seconds")
    
print("\nCross-validation complete!")
print("New fine-tuned model training time (seconds):", New_fine_tuned_train_time)

all_preds_new_1 = []   # Stores predicted labels for each fold
all_labels_new_1 = []  # Stores true labels for each fold

# Extract labels for stratification because it requires labels for equal proportion of classes cross folds
labels_array = np.array([tensor[-1].cpu().numpy() for tensor in all_data_tensors]) # Assuming last tensor is labels

# Cross-validation loop
for fold, (train_idx, eval_idx) in enumerate(scv.split(np.zeros(len(labels_array)), labels_array)):

    print(f"Evaluating fold {fold + 1}/{n_splits}...")

    model_new_1.eval()  # Set model to evaluation mode

    # Create evaluation dataset and dataloader for this fold
    eval_data_scv = torch.utils.data.Subset(all_data_tensors, eval_idx)
    eval_sampler_scv = SequentialSampler(eval_data_scv)
    eval_dataloader_scv = DataLoader(eval_data_scv, sampler=eval_sampler_scv, batch_size=Batch_size)

    fold_preds_new_1 = []  # Store predictions for this fold
    fold_labels_new_1 = []  # Store true labels for this fold

    # Run evaluation without tracking gradients
    with torch.no_grad():
        for batch in tqdm(eval_dataloader_scv, desc=f"Evaluating Fold {fold + 1}", total=int(len(eval_data_scv)/Batch_size)+1):

            batch = tuple(s.to(device) for s in batch)  # Move batch to GPU/CPU
            input_ids, input_mask, input_types, labels = batch

            # Forward pass (ensure correct argument names)
            output = model_new_1(input_ids=input_ids, attention_mask=input_mask, labels=None)

            # Store predictions and labels
            fold_preds_new_1.append(output.logits.detach().cpu().numpy())
            fold_labels_new_1.append(labels.cpu().numpy())

    # Store predictions per fold
    all_preds_new_1.append(np.concatenate(fold_preds_new_1, axis=0))  # Convert list of batches to array
    all_labels_new_1.append(np.concatenate(fold_labels_new_1, axis=0))  # Convert list of labels to array
